Communicated by:
ProMED from HealthMap Alerts

[This suspiciously sounds like a street drug known to South Africans as Strawberry Quick. It is often sold by "sweet vendors" who are frequently found around the schools. Strawberry Quick is a combination of sugar, food coloring, flavors and crystal meth. Symptoms are reported to include chattiness, nervousness, dry mouth, dilated pupils, extreme energy followed by chronic fatigue, paranoia, jaw clenching, increased heart rate, excessive sweating, increased libido, and in severe cases may include hallucinations. There may also be direct effects on the heart, circulation, and neurological systems.

Some sweet concoctions may include amphetamines, alone or in combination with the meth. If amphetamines are the only drug (no crystal meth) then clinical signs may show an increase in heart rate, palpitations, sweating, nervousness, possible hallucinations and even convulsions.

The combination of crystal meth and ampehtamines could be deadly to children, and possibly adults. The child's smaller size means the dose of drugs is potentially more toxic and detrimental to the child.

The Anti Drug Alliance SA [South Africa, also known as ADA-SA] encourages parents to teach children never to accept sweets from anyone other than their family and to never accept or purchase sweets from street vendors. The Anti Drug Alliance SA also encourages parents to know the drugs and their clinical signs in case a child displays signs, so they understand what is happening, where and how to seek immediate medical attention, and to be able to explain in clear terms what signs the child display. - Mod.TG

